the discovery of oil. The existence of oil had a major impact on the economy. Mineral extraction of Syria began in the north in the Hazaa fields in early 1938. The large Arab Petroleum Company (AAPC) operates the Hazaa’s Oil field, which has been the largest crude oil field in Syria. AAPC had extended its activities in Syria until 1973. Later, the production reach 5 million tonnes per year and employs 35,000 peoples. By the end of the ‘70s, Syria made progressive efforts to encourage the participation of the private sector in the oil sector. The policy was reflected in the offer by the Syrian government of all the oil companies operating in the country a three-year grace period to improve their production efficiency and develop investment, followed by more incentives for the same companies after 1980. By the early 90’s it was clear that the implementation of the economic reform program and the private initiative policies have failed. The ‘privatization’ of the oil industry was one of the many failures of the economic program [19].
The oil industry of Syria was not immune to civil war that started in 2011. Since oil production is controlled by Iraq and also the scope of the Syrian civil war is regional, oil production collapsed as a result of the reduction of foreign exchange inflows, financial deficits, and other consequences of sanctions and isolation of Syria, which lasted for more than a decade.
